To solve the non-homogeneous system of linear equations, we can use the method of substitution or elimination. In this case, we will use the elimination method.

First, we will eliminate y from the first two equations. To do this, we will add the first and second equations:

\begin{align*}
  (2x - y + z) + (x + y - 2z) &= 7 + 4\\
  3x - z &= 11
\end{align*}

Now, we will eliminate y from the second and third equations. To do this, we will subtract the second equation from the third equation:

\begin{align*}
  (3x + y + z) - (x + y - 2z) &= 12 - 4\\
  2x + 3z &= 8
\end{align*}

Now we have a system of two equations with two variables:

\begin{align*}
  3x - z &= 11\\
  2x + 3z &= 8
\end{align*}

We can now eliminate x from these two equations. To do this, we will multiply the first equation by 2 and the second equation by 3, and then subtract the first equation from the second equation:

\begin{align*}
  (6x - 2z) - (6x + 9z) &= 22 - 24\\
  -11z &= -2
\end{align*}

Now we can solve for z:

\begin{align*}
  z &= \frac{-2}{-11}\\
  z &= \frac{2}{11}
\end{align*}

Now that we have the value of z, we can substitute it back into the equation 3x - z = 11 to find the value of x:

\begin{align*}
  3x - \frac{2}{11} &= 11\\
  3x &= 11 + \frac{2}{11}\\
  3x &= \frac{121}{11}\\
  x &= \frac{121}{33}
\end{align*}

Finally, we can substitute the values of x and z back into the equation x + y - 2z = 4 to find the value of y:

\begin{align*}
  \frac{121}{33} + y - 2\left(\frac{2}{11}\right) &= 4\\
  y - \frac{4}{11} &= 4 - \frac{121}{33}\\
  y &= \frac{4}{1} - \frac{4}{11} + \frac{121}{33}\\
  y &= \frac{44 - 4 + 121}{33}\\
  y &= \frac{161}{33}
\end{align*}

So the solution to the non-homogeneous system of linear equations is:

\begin{align*}
  x &= \frac{121}{33}\\
  y &= \frac{161}{33}\\
  z &= \frac{2}{11}
\end{align*}
